<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos pumila </i>is a prostrate to mounded, evergreen, sclerophyllous shrub. Leaves are spreading from the stems, and they have upper shiny-green, convex surfaces and lower gray-tomentose surfaces. They have wedge-shaped bases. Plants lack lignotubers, but branches touching the ground readily root. Seeds collect in a seed bank as stones. Seeds germinate after heat scarification, though heat is not required for germination. <br/>
<br/>
The species is adapted to moderately long fire return intervals (around 100 years). Stands require periodic fire to maintain current species composition. Infrequent fire results in shrubs being replaced by trees and in decreased seed bank quality, whereas frequent fire tends to convert the stands to coastal scrub or grassland. Maritime chaparral stands have a historic fire cycle of 10-100 years (Greenlee and Langenheim 1990, Van Dyke et al. 2001); however, the lower end of this range is more likely 40-50 years for this alliance (M. Vasey, pers. com 2007). Prescribed burns are recommended to reduce tree invasion (Greenlee and Langenheim 1990, Van Dyke et al. 2001). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos pumila </i>(a CNPS list 1B plant) creates stands that support at least five rare plants. <i>Arctostaphylos hookeri </i>ssp. <i>hookeri, Chorizanthe pungens </i>var. <i>pungens, Ericameria fasciculata, </i>and <i>Piperia yadonii </i>are CNPS list 1B plants <i>. Ceanothus cuneatus </i>var. <i>rigidus </i>is a CNPS list 4 plant. <i>Chorizanthe pungens </i>var. <i>pungens </i>is federally listed as threatened, and <i>P. yadonii </i>is listed as endangered. Stands may also include <i>Gilia tenuiflora </i>ssp. <i>arenaria </i>(a CNPS list 1B plant) (M. Vasey, pers. comm. 2007). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands occur in the Central California Coast (261B) as at Fort Ord Military Reservation on Bureau of Land Management lands. They tend to occur on sandy soil closer to the coast than adjacent stands of the <i>Arctostaphylos hookeri</i> and <i>Arctostaphylos</i> (<i>crustacea, tomentosa</i>) alliances. </div>
</div>

	

    
